## 1. Railway Maintenance Domain

### 1.1 ECM Framework (EU 2019/779)

The **Entity in Charge of Maintenance (ECM)** framework establishes legal responsibilities for railway vehicle maintenance across European railway networks. While Dubai Metro is outside EU jurisdiction, the ECM framework represents industry best practice and provides a compliance-ready architecture.

#### 1.1.1 ECM Function Mapping

| Function | Responsibility | MMS V1.0 Feature | V1.0 Status |
|----------|----------------|------------------|-------------|
| **ECM-F1** | Maintenance Management | Dashboard KPIs, compliance tracking | Visualization only |
| **ECM-F2** | Maintenance Development | Interval definitions, plan visualization | Mock data display |
| **ECM-F3** | Fleet Maintenance Management | Real-time fleet status, conflict detection | Conflict indicators |
| **ECM-F4** | Maintenance Delivery | Work order visualization, depot allocation | Visual representation |

#### 1.1.2 ECM Compliance Requirements

| Requirement | ECM Article | MMS V1.0 Implementation | V1.1+ Roadmap |
|-------------|-------------|------------------------|---------------|
| Risk assessment | Art. 5.2 | Conflict detection, overdue warnings | Automated alerts |
| Competence management | Art. 5.3 | Not implemented | Resource skill tracking |
| Documentation | Art. 5.4 | Not implemented | Audit trail logging |
| Performance monitoring | Art. 5.5 | KPI display | Fleet availability metrics |

#### 1.1.3 ECM Traceability Requirements (Future)

Full ECM compliance requires traceability of all maintenance decisions:

- Immutable audit logs of all scheduling decisions
- Justification records for allocation recommendations
- Historical mileage tracking with timestamps
- Decision override justifications

**V1.0 Scope:** Visualization only. Audit trail deferred to V1.1.

---

### 1.2 RAMS Compliance (EN 50126-1)

**RAMS** = Reliability, Availability, Maintainability, Safety

EN 50126-1:2017 defines the railway RAMS lifecycle and requirements. MMS visualizes RAMS metrics but does not implement automated RAMS analysis in V1.0.

#### 1.2.1 RAMS Metric Definitions

| Aspect | Standard | Definition | MMS V1.0 Feature |
|--------|----------|------------|------------------|
| **Reliability** | EN 50126-1 Section 6 | Probability that system performs intended function under stated conditions for specified period | MTBF display |
| **Availability** | EN 50126-1 Section 7 | Ability to be in a state to perform a required function at a given instant | Fleet availability % |
| **Maintainability** | EN 50126-1 Section 8 | Probability that maintenance can be performed within stated time | MTTR display |
| **Safety** | EN 50126-1 Section 9 | Freedom from unacceptable risk of harm | Critical task priority |

#### 1.2.2 RAMS Targets

| Metric | Formula | Target | Critical Threshold |
|--------|---------|--------|-------------------|
| Fleet Availability | (Fit Trains / Total Trains) x 100 | >= 97% | < 95% |
| MTBF | Total Operating Hours / Number of Failures | Operator-defined | Operator-defined |
| MTTR | Total Downtime Hours / Number of Repairs | <= 24 hours | > 48 hours |
| Schedule Adherence | (On-Time Maintenance / Scheduled Maintenance) x 100 | >= 95% | < 90% |

---

### 1.3 EN 15380 Railway Terminology

All user-facing labels in MMS MUST use EN 15380 compliant terminology. This ensures industry credibility and operator familiarity.

#### 1.3.1 Mandatory Term Usage

| EN 15380 Term | Definition | NOT Acceptable |
|---------------|------------|----------------|
| Rolling Stock | Railway vehicles requiring maintenance | Vehicle, Asset, Unit |
| Fleet | Group of rolling stock sharing manufacturer/model | Group, Class, Collection |
| Depot | Designated maintenance facility | Garage, Workshop, Station |
| Train Fitness | Binary operational readiness (fit/unfit) | Availability, Health, Status |
| Run Assignment | Daily allocation of train IDs to routes | Dispatch, Schedule, Trip |
| Dead Running | Non-revenue movement between locations | Empty movement, Repositioning |
| Service | Scheduled revenue-generating journey | Route, Trip, Run |
| Mileage Balancing | Strategy to equalize wear across fleet | Usage balancing, Wear distribution |

#### 1.3.2 Maintenance Terminology

| Term | Definition | Context |
|------|------------|---------|
| PM (Preventive Maintenance) | Scheduled maintenance at defined intervals | Time or mileage-based |
| CM (Corrective Maintenance) | Unscheduled repair after failure detection | Reactive |
| CBM (Condition-Based Maintenance) | Triggered by condition monitoring | Future: sensor-based |
| Overhaul | Major refurbishment restoring to original condition | Resets maintenance counters |
| Heavy Maintenance | Significant maintenance requiring extended depot stay | Multi-day duration |

