## 5. Maintenance Level Mapping

### 5.1 Authoritative Mapping Table

This is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for maintenance level terminology. All other documentation must reference this table.

| Internal Code | Railway Term | User Display | Interval (km) | Tolerance | Duration | Man-Hours | Tracks | Est. Cost |
|--------------|--------------|--------------|---------------|-----------|----------|-----------|--------|-----------|
| A | PM1 | A-Check | 10,000 | +/- 2,000 | 4 hours | 8 | 1 | $2,500 |
| B | PM2 | B-Check | 50,000 | +/- 5,000 | 16 hours | 32 | 1 | $8,500 |
| C | PM3 | C-Check | 200,000 | +/- 20,000 | 72 hours | 160 | 1 | $45,000 |
| D | HM | D-Overhaul | 800,000 | +/- 50,000 | 480 hours | 1,200 | 2 | $180,000 |

#### 5.1.1 Terminology Key

| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| **PM1** | Preventive Maintenance Level 1 (Light) |
| **PM2** | Preventive Maintenance Level 2 (Intermediate) |
| **PM3** | Preventive Maintenance Level 3 (Scheduled) |
| **HM** | Heavy Maintenance / Major Overhaul |
| **OVH** | Full Overhaul / Refurbishment (resets all counters) |

#### 5.1.2 Usage Rules

1. **Internal code (A/B/C/D)**: Used in type definitions and database
2. **Railway term (PM1/PM2/PM3/HM)**: Used in domain discussions and documentation
3. **User display (A-Check, etc.)**: Used in UI labels and user-facing text

---

### 5.2 Maintenance Cascade

Maintenance levels follow a cascade pattern where higher levels include lower level tasks:

```
Fleet Type (e.g., Alstom Red Line)
 |
 +-- Maintenance Profile
     |
     +-- PM1 / A-Check (every 10,000 km)
     |   Duration: 4 hours
     |   Tasks: Inspection, fluid top-up, brake check
     |
     +-- PM2 / B-Check (every 50,000 km)
     |   Duration: 16 hours
     |   Tasks: Component replacement, deep inspection
     |   Note: INCLUDES PM1 tasks
     |
     +-- PM3 / C-Check (every 200,000 km)
     |   Duration: 72 hours
     |   Tasks: Major component inspection, bogie work
     |   Note: INCLUDES PM1 + PM2 tasks
     |
     +-- HM / D-Overhaul (every 800,000 km)
         Duration: 480 hours (20 days)
         Tasks: Complete refurbishment
         Note: RESETS maintenance counters
```

---

### 5.3 Maintenance Triggers

| Trigger Type | Description | Best For | Limitations |
|--------------|-------------|----------|-------------|
| Time-based | Calendar intervals (e.g., monthly) | Simple assets, regulatory compliance | Over/under maintenance |
| Mileage-based | Odometer intervals (primary) | Wear-dependent components | Tracking complexity |
| Condition-based | Sensor thresholds | Critical components | Sensor infrastructure |
| Hybrid | Combined triggers | Most applications | Implementation complexity |

**V1.0 Implementation:** Mileage-based only (primary trigger type for Dubai Metro).

---

## 6. Domain Rules

### 6.1 Hard Constraints (Never Violate)

These constraints MUST be satisfied. Solver solutions that violate hard constraints are INVALID.

| ID | Rule | Rationale | Enforcement |
|----|------|-----------|-------------|
| HC-1 | Unfit trains are NEVER assigned to service | Safety-critical | Pre-filter in queries |
| HC-2 | Maintenance windows are immutable | Planned downtime is scheduled | Block overlapping allocations |
| HC-3 | Aptitude requirements are binary | Route compatibility is fixed | Pre-filter by capability |
| HC-4 | Depot capacity is physical | Cannot exceed track slots | Resource constraint |
| HC-5 | Service cannot be cancelled for balancing | Operations > Optimization | Priority ordering |

### 6.2 Soft Constraints (Optimize Within)

These constraints are PREFERENCES. Solver optimizes these within hard constraint boundaries.

| ID | Rule | Weight | Description |
|----|------|--------|-------------|
| SC-1 | Km balancing priority | 1000 (HIGH) | Under-running trains should get high-km services |
| SC-2 | Dead running minimization | 100 (MEDIUM) | Prefer trains ending near next service start |
| SC-3 | Maintenance depot proximity | 10 (LOW) | Schedule services ending near maintenance depot |
| SC-4 | Crew familiarity | N/A | Same crews prefer same train types (not in V1.0) |

### 6.3 Tolerance Windows

| Maintenance Level | Tolerance | Overrun Warning | Critical Overrun |
|-------------------|-----------|-----------------|------------------|
| PM1 / A-Check | +/- 2,000 km | At 95% of interval | At 105% of interval |
| PM2 / B-Check | +/- 5,000 km | At 95% of interval | At 105% of interval |
| PM3 / C-Check | +/- 20,000 km | At 95% of interval | At 105% of interval |
| HM / D-Overhaul | +/- 50,000 km | At 95% of interval | At 105% of interval |

---

## 7. Train State Machine

### 7.1 State Diagram

```
    +-----------------------------------------------+
    |                                               |
    v                                               |
+-------+     +------------+     +------------+     |
|  FIT  |---->| IN-SERVICE |---->| AVAILABLE  |----+
+---+---+     +------------+     +-----+------+
    |                                  |
    |         +------------+           |
    +-------->|   UNFIT    |<----------+
              +-----+------+
                    |
                    v
              +------------+
              |MAINTENANCE |
              +-----+------+
                    |
                    v
              +------------+
              |    FIT     |
              +------------+
```

### 7.2 State Definitions

| State | Definition | Allowed Transitions |
|-------|------------|---------------------|
| **FIT** | Train is operationally ready | IN-SERVICE, UNFIT |
| **IN-SERVICE** | Train actively running revenue service | AVAILABLE |
| **AVAILABLE** | Train fit but not currently assigned | IN-SERVICE, UNFIT |
| **UNFIT** | Train requires maintenance | MAINTENANCE |
| **MAINTENANCE** | Train undergoing maintenance | FIT |

### 7.3 Transition Rules

| From | To | Trigger | Guard Condition |
|------|-----|---------|-----------------|
| FIT | IN-SERVICE | Service allocation | Valid service assignment |
| IN-SERVICE | AVAILABLE | Service completion | End of service |
| AVAILABLE | IN-SERVICE | Service allocation | Valid service assignment |
| AVAILABLE | UNFIT | Maintenance due | Km threshold reached |
| FIT | UNFIT | Maintenance due | Km threshold reached |
| UNFIT | MAINTENANCE | Depot arrival | Track available |
| MAINTENANCE | FIT | Maintenance complete | All work completed |

---

## 8. Planning Hierarchy

### 8.1 Multi-Level Structure

```
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
|                MASTER PLAN (Annual/Multi-Year)               |
|  - Resource allocation across contract period                |
|  - Major overhaul scheduling (HM/D-Check)                    |
|  - Budget planning and forecasting                           |
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
|                     MONTHLY PLAN                             |
|  - Medium-scale repairs allocation (PM2/PM3)                 |
|  - Workload balancing across weeks                           |
|  - Resource adjustment and reallocation                      |
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
|                      WEEKLY PLAN                             |
|  - Detailed work orders                                      |
|  - Staff rostering and track allocation                      |
|  - Parts requisition                                         |
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
|                      DAILY PLAN                              |
|  - Execution scheduling (PM1/A-Check)                        |
|  - Real-time adjustments                                     |
|  - Emergency response coordination                           |
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
```

### 8.2 Time Zone Concept (Frozen Periods)

| Time Horizon | Zone Status | Constraint Type | Allowed Changes |
|--------------|-------------|-----------------|-----------------|
| T > 12 weeks | **Liquid** | Soft | Structure, Volume, Frequency |
| T-12 to T-7 weeks | **Slushy** | Medium | Timing, Resource Allocation |
| T-7 weeks to T-48h | **Frozen** | Hard | Emergency Only (High Cost) |
| T < 48 hours | **Execution** | Fixed | None (break-fix only) |

### 8.3 MMS LOD Mapping

| Planning Level | MMS LOD | Zoom Range | Use Case |
|----------------|---------|------------|----------|
| Master Plan | MACRO | < 0.5x | Strategic overview, multi-year view |
| Monthly Plan | MESO | 0.5x - 1.0x | Tactical planning, quarterly view |
| Weekly Plan | MESO | 1.0x - 2.0x | Operational planning, monthly view |
| Daily Plan | MICRO | > 2.0x | Execution detail, weekly view |

---

## 9. Glossary

### 9.1 Railway Domain Terms

| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **CBM** | Condition-Based Maintenance - maintenance triggered by condition monitoring |
| **Dead Running** | Non-revenue movement of rolling stock between locations |
| **Depot** | Designated maintenance facility for rolling stock |
| **ECM** | Entity in Charge of Maintenance (EU regulatory framework) |
| **Fleet** | Group of rolling stock sharing manufacturer/model characteristics |
| **Mileage Balancing** | Strategy to equalize wear across fleet by allocation optimization |
| **RAMS** | Reliability, Availability, Maintainability, Safety |
| **Rolling Stock** | Railway vehicles (trains, carriages) requiring maintenance |
| **Run Assignment** | Daily allocation of train IDs to scheduled services |
| **Train Fitness** | Binary operational readiness status (fit/unfit) |

### 9.2 Maintenance Terms

| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **HM** | Heavy Maintenance - major overhaul requiring extended depot time |
| **MDBF** | Mean Distance Between Failures |
| **MTBF** | Mean Time Between Failures |
| **MTTR** | Mean Time To Repair |
| **OVH** | Overhaul - complete refurbishment that resets counters |
| **PM1/PM2/PM3** | Preventive Maintenance levels 1, 2, 3 |

### 9.3 Technical Terms

| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **CP** | Constraint Programming (optimization technique) |
| **LOD** | Level of Detail (visualization granularity) |
| **MIP** | Mixed Integer Programming (optimization technique) |
| **SoA** | Structure of Arrays (data layout pattern) |

### 9.4 MMS-Specific Terms

| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **Blend Zone** | Zoom range where two LOD layers crossfade |
| **MACRO Layer** | Heatmap view at zoom < 0.5x |
| **MESO Layer** | Task block view at zoom 0.5x - 2.0x |
| **MICRO Layer** | Detailed card view at zoom > 2.0x |
| **Semantic Zoom** | Google Earth-style LOD switching based on zoom level |
| **TaskRender** | Computed task data for canvas rendering |

